window.MODULES=window.MODULES||{};window.MODULES["pulmonary-hypertension"]={"slug": "pulmonary-hypertension", "title": "Pulmonary Hypertension: From Hemodynamic Definition to Group-Specific Therapy", "tagline": "A fellowship-level framework for defining, classifying, and treating pulmonary hypertension by mechanism and the right ventricle, not by pressure alone.", "level": 3, "readMin": 32, "takeaways": ["Under the 2022 ESC/ERS definition, pulmonary hypertension is a resting mean pulmonary artery pressure (mPAP) above 20 mmHg; precapillary disease additionally requires PAWP 15 mmHg or less AND pulmonary vascular resistance (PVR) above 2 Wood units, and every therapeutic decision flows from correctly assigning the patient to one of the five WHO groups.", "Right heart catheterization is mandatory before labeling any patient with pulmonary arterial hypertension (PAH) and before starting PAH-specific therapy; echocardiography and clinical gestalt are for screening and pretest probability, never for the diagnosis.", "Acute vasoreactivity testing with inhaled nitric oxide identifies the small minority of idiopathic, heritable, or drug-induced PAH patients who may respond durably to high-dose calcium channel blockers; a positive response (Sitbon criteria) is a fall in mPAP of at least 10 mmHg to an absolute mPAP of 40 mmHg or less with preserved or increased cardiac output.", "Group 1 PAH is treated with upfront combination therapy across the endothelin, nitric oxide, and prostacyclin pathways, guided by validated multiparameter risk stratification (ESC/ERS 4-strata, REVEAL Lite 2), with sotatercept now added as an activin-signaling anti-remodeling agent.", "Do NOT treat Group 2 (left heart disease) or Group 3 (lung disease/hypoxia) pulmonary hypertension with Group 1 PAH vasodilators outside of a trial; the sole nuanced exception is inhaled treprostinil for PH-ILD, and indiscriminate vasodilation risks flash pulmonary edema (Group 2) and worsened V/Q matching and hypoxemia (Group 3).", "The right ventricle, not the pulmonary pressure, is the therapeutic target: RV-PA coupling determines symptoms and survival, and pulmonary pressures can paradoxically fall as the failing RV can no longer generate them. Suspected CTEPH (Group 4) must reach an expert center because it is potentially curable by pulmonary endarterectomy."], "sections": [{"id": "learning-objectives", "title": "Learning Objectives", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "This module moves the internal medicine resident from a pressure-centric view of pulmonary hypertension (PH) toward a fellowship-level, mechanism- and right-ventricle-centered framework. PH is not a diagnosis; it is a hemodynamic state with dozens of causes, and the entire clinical craft lies in assigning the correct WHO group before any drug is written."}, {"type": "list", "depth": 1, "head": ["By the end you should be able to:"], "items": ["State the 2022 ESC/ERS hemodynamic definition and separate <strong>pre-capillary</strong>, <strong>isolated post-capillary</strong>, and <strong>combined post/pre-capillary</strong> PH by PAWP and PVR.", "Recite the five WHO groups and their major subcategories, and explain why group assignment dictates therapy.", "Build a diagnostic algorithm from echo pretest probability through V/Q scan to confirmatory right heart catheterization (RHC).", "Perform and interpret <strong>acute vasoreactivity testing</strong> and identify the rare CCB-eligible patient.", "Prescribe the four PAH drug classes by mechanism, dose, contraindication, and monitoring, and apply risk stratification to choose upfront combination therapy.", "Explain why Groups 2 and 3 are managed by treating the underlying disease, not by vasodilating the pulmonary bed."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 2, "text": "<strong>Framing for the consult.</strong> When a resident calls with \"elevated PA pressures on echo,\" the fellow's first three questions are always: What is the left atrial pressure (Group 2)? What is the lung parenchyma and oxygenation (Group 3)? Has anyone excluded chronic thromboembolic disease with a V/Q scan (Group 4)? Group 1 PAH is a diagnosis of careful exclusion."}]}, {"id": "definition-hemodynamics", "title": "Hemodynamic Definition", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Pulmonary hypertension is defined hemodynamically, at rest, by right heart catheterization. The 2022 ESC/ERS guideline lowered the threshold from the historic mPAP of 25 mmHg to <strong>mPAP greater than 20 mmHg</strong>, reflecting that the upper limit of normal is roughly 20 mmHg (normal mPAP is about 14 mmHg, and mean plus two standard deviations approaches 20) and that mildly elevated pressures carry prognostic weight."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 1, "entries": [{"term": "mPAP", "def": "Mean pulmonary artery pressure. PH is defined as >20 mmHg at rest. Normal is approximately 14 +/- 3 mmHg."}, {"term": "PAWP (PCWP)", "def": "Pulmonary artery wedge (occlusion) pressure, a surrogate for left atrial pressure. The dividing line between pre-capillary and post-capillary disease: <=15 mmHg is pre-capillary; >15 mmHg is post-capillary."}, {"term": "PVR", "def": "Pulmonary vascular resistance = (mPAP - PAWP) / cardiac output, expressed in Wood units (WU). The 2022 threshold for pulmonary vascular disease is >2 WU (lowered from 3 WU)."}, {"term": "TPG / DPG", "def": "Transpulmonary gradient (mPAP - PAWP) and diastolic pulmonary gradient (PA diastolic - PAWP). Historically used to flag a pulmonary vascular component in post-capillary PH; PVR has largely supplanted them."}]}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "label": "Hemodynamic phenotypes (2022 ESC/ERS)", "head": ["Phenotype", "mPAP", "PAWP", "PVR", "Prototype groups"], "rows": [["Pre-capillary PH", ">20 mmHg", "<=15 mmHg", ">2 WU", "Groups 1, 3, 4, and most of 5"], ["Isolated post-capillary (IpcPH)", ">20 mmHg", ">15 mmHg", "<=2 WU", "Group 2 (left heart)"], ["Combined post- and pre-capillary (CpcPH)", ">20 mmHg", ">15 mmHg", ">2 WU", "Group 2 with superimposed vascular remodeling"], ["Exercise PH", "mPAP/CO slope >3 mmHg/L/min between rest and exercise", "-", "-", "Early / unmasked disease"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 2, "text": "<strong>Mnemonic.</strong> \"20-15-2\": mPAP >20 makes PH; PAWP >15 makes it post-capillary; PVR >2 makes it a pulmonary vascular disease. You need all three numbers off one catheterization to phenotype the patient."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "<strong>Why the thresholds moved.</strong> Registry and cohort data (including the work behind the 6th World Symposium) showed that patients with mPAP 21 to 24 mmHg and PVR 2 to 3 WU have measurably worse outcomes than truly normal subjects. The change does not mean these patients are treated as PAH; it means they are watched and worked up rather than dismissed. The 2 WU threshold particularly reshapes the CpcPH population in heart failure."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 2, "text": "<strong>Wedge pitfalls.</strong> A falsely low wedge (over-wedging, reading during a large a-wave, or a patient who is volume-depleted from diuretics) can misclassify Group 2 as Group 1 and lead to inappropriate vasodilator therapy. Confirm the wedge with an oximetry step-up saturation or a directly measured LVEDP when the number does not fit the clinical picture, and consider a fluid challenge or exercise if occult HFpEF is suspected."}]}, {"id": "classification-who-groups", "title": "The Five WHO Groups", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "The clinical classification groups PH by shared mechanism, natural history, and (critically) response to therapy. Getting the group right is the single most consequential decision in PH medicine."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 1, "entries": [{"term": "Group 1 — Pulmonary arterial hypertension (PAH)", "def": "Pre-capillary disease of the small pulmonary arteries. Subtypes: idiopathic (IPAH), heritable (BMPR2 and others), drug/toxin-induced (methamphetamine, dasatinib, older anorexigens), associated with connective tissue disease (especially systemic sclerosis), HIV, portal hypertension (portopulmonary), congenital heart disease, and schistosomiasis. Includes the distinct subsets PVOD/PCH (veno-occlusive) and long-term-responder PAH."}, {"term": "Group 2 — PH due to left heart disease", "def": "The most common cause worldwide. HFrEF, HFpEF, valvular disease (mitral and aortic), and congenital/acquired inflow or outflow obstruction. Post-capillary physiology (PAWP >15). Treatment is of the left heart, not the pulmonary bed."}, {"term": "Group 3 — PH due to lung disease and/or hypoxia", "def": "COPD, interstitial lung disease, combined pulmonary fibrosis and emphysema, sleep-disordered breathing, alveolar hypoventilation, chronic high-altitude exposure, developmental lung disorders. Usually mild PH driven by hypoxic vasoconstriction and vascular destruction."}, {"term": "Group 4 — PH due to pulmonary artery obstruction", "def": "Chronic thromboembolic pulmonary hypertension (CTEPH) and other obstructions (tumor, arteritis, congenital stenosis). Potentially curable by pulmonary endarterectomy. Diagnosis hinges on a V/Q scan."}, {"term": "Group 5 — Unclear/multifactorial mechanisms", "def": "Hematologic (chronic hemolytic anemia, myeloproliferative disorders), systemic (sarcoidosis, pulmonary Langerhans cell histiocytosis), metabolic (glycogen storage, Gaucher), chronic renal failure on dialysis, fibrosing mediastinitis, and complex congenital disease."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "text": "<strong>Mnemonic for the five groups.</strong> \"Arteries, Atrium, Airways, Anti-coagulate, Assorted\": 1 = small Arteries (PAH), 2 = left Atrium/left heart, 3 = Airways/lung, 4 = clots you Anti-coagulate (CTEPH), 5 = Assorted/multifactorial."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "<strong>PVOD/PCH deserves respect.</strong> Pulmonary veno-occlusive disease and pulmonary capillary hemangiomatosis sit within Group 1 but behave dangerously: aggressive PAH vasodilators, especially prostacyclins, can precipitate fulminant pulmonary edema because the obstruction is post-capillary at the venular level. Clues are low DLCO out of proportion, hypoxemia, and the radiographic triad of septal lines, centrilobular ground-glass, and mediastinal adenopathy. These patients are transplant referrals, not aggressive up-titration candidates."}, {"type": "linkout", "depth": 1, "text": "For the WHO classification schematic and the histopathology of plexiform lesions and veno-occlusive change, a labeled figure is worth reviewing alongside this text.", "url": "https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/", "label": "Classification and pathology figures (PMC)"}]}, {"id": "pathobiology", "title": "Pathobiology and the Physiology of Progression", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "In PAH the disease is in the small pulmonary arteries: endothelial dysfunction, smooth muscle and adventitial proliferation, in-situ thrombosis, and the pathognomonic plexiform lesion progressively obliterate the cross-sectional area of the pulmonary vascular bed. Three signaling axes are deranged and map directly onto the drug classes."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "label": "The three classic pathways (and the fourth, new one)", "head": ["Pathway", "Derangement in PAH", "Net effect", "Drug class that targets it"], "rows": [["Endothelin", "Excess endothelin-1 via ET-A/ET-B receptors", "Vasoconstriction + proliferation", "Endothelin receptor antagonists (ERAs)"], ["Nitric oxide / cGMP", "Reduced NO, low cGMP", "Loss of vasodilation/antiproliferation", "PDE5 inhibitors, sGC stimulator (riociguat)"], ["Prostacyclin", "Reduced prostacyclin synthase", "Vasoconstriction, platelet aggregation, proliferation", "Prostacyclin analogues and IP-receptor agonist"], ["Activin / BMPR2 (new)", "Excess activin/GDF signaling, loss of BMPR2 restraint", "Unchecked vascular cell proliferation", "Sotatercept (activin ligand trap)"]]}, {"type": "p", "depth": 2, "text": "The BMPR2 pathway is central to heritable PAH and to the rationale for sotatercept: loss-of-function BMPR2 mutations remove a brake on proliferation, while excess activin-type ligands push the accelerator. Sotatercept is a fusion protein that traps these activin ligands, rebalancing pro- and anti-proliferative signaling. This is the first agent designed to reverse remodeling rather than simply vasodilate."}, {"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "The clinically decisive point is that the right ventricle (RV), not the pulmonary artery, is the organ that fails and kills. As PVR rises, the thin-walled RV first hypertrophies and dilates to preserve stroke volume (adaptive remodeling), then uncouples from the load (maladaptive remodeling): RV-PA coupling, measured as the ratio of end-systolic elastance to arterial elastance (Ees/Ea), falls, cardiac output drops, the RV dilates and becomes ischemic, and functional tricuspid regurgitation and interventricular septal bowing impair LV filling."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "<strong>Pressures can fall as the patient dies.</strong> A late, failing RV cannot generate high pulmonary pressures; a declining mPAP with a rising right atrial pressure, falling cardiac output, and worsening symptoms is an ominous sign of RV-PA uncoupling, not improvement. This is why we prognosticate with RA pressure, cardiac index, and RV function, not with PA systolic pressure. Treat the ventricle, not the number."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 2, "text": "<strong>Pearl.</strong> A pericardial effusion on echo in PAH is a marker of elevated right atrial pressure and a poor-prognosis sign; do not drain it reflexively, as pericardiocentesis in decompensated RV failure can precipitate hemodynamic collapse."}]}, {"id": "presentation-screening", "title": "Presentation and Screening", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Symptoms are nonspecific and late: exertional dyspnea, fatigue, and reduced exercise capacity dominate early; exertional chest pain (RV ischemia), presyncope or syncope (fixed low output), and lower-extremity edema and ascites (RV failure) mark advanced disease. The diagnostic delay from symptom onset often exceeds two years, which is why targeted screening of high-risk populations matters."}, {"type": "list", "depth": 2, "head": ["Exam findings that should raise suspicion:"], "items": ["Loud, palpable P2; right-sided S3 or S4", "Left parasternal (RV) heave", "Holosystolic murmur of tricuspid regurgitation that augments with inspiration (Carvallo sign)", "Elevated JVP with prominent v wave; hepatomegaly, pulsatile liver, ascites, peripheral edema", "In portopulmonary and CTD-PAH, the stigmata of the underlying disease"]}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "label": "Who to screen actively", "head": ["Population", "Rationale / tool"], "rows": [["Systemic sclerosis", "Annual screening with the DETECT algorithm or echo + PFTs (DLCO) + NT-proBNP; high incidence of PAH"], ["BMPR2 or other pathogenic mutation carriers / first-degree relatives of HPAH", "Periodic echo screening"], ["Portal hypertension being evaluated for liver transplant", "Screening echo; portopulmonary HTN affects candidacy and peri-transplant risk"], ["HIV, prior anorexigen or methamphetamine exposure", "Screen if symptomatic"], ["Survivors of acute PE with persistent dyspnea at 3+ months", "Screen for CTEPH with V/Q scan"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 2, "text": "<strong>Never anchor.</strong> Unexplained dyspnea plus a normal chest film and \"normal\" spirometry with a disproportionately low DLCO is PH until proven otherwise. An isolated low DLCO is one of the most commonly missed early clues, particularly in scleroderma and PVOD."}]}, {"id": "diagnostic-algorithm", "title": "Diagnostic Algorithm", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "The workup is a deliberate sequence: establish pretest probability, exclude the common groups (2 and 3), mandatorily exclude CTEPH (4), then confirm and phenotype with RHC. Skipping the V/Q scan is the classic error that lets curable CTEPH be misdiagnosed as inoperable IPAH."}, {"type": "steps", "depth": 1, "head": ["Stepwise workup"], "items": ["<strong>Transthoracic echocardiogram</strong> — the screening test. Estimate PASP from the TR jet (4v-squared + RA pressure), and integrate RV size and function (TAPSE, RV S'), RA area, septal flattening (D-shaped LV in systole = pressure overload), and pericardial effusion into a low/intermediate/high echo probability of PH.", "<strong>Assess for Group 2</strong> — history, LV function, diastolic parameters (E/e', LA volume), valvular disease. HFpEF is the great mimic.", "<strong>Assess for Group 3</strong> — PFTs with DLCO, ABG/oximetry, and high-resolution chest CT for parenchymal lung disease and sleep study if indicated.", "<strong>Ventilation/perfusion (V/Q) scan for ALL suspected pre-capillary PH</strong> — a normal V/Q effectively excludes CTEPH; segmental mismatched defects mandate CT pulmonary angiography and referral to a CTEPH center. V/Q is more sensitive than CTPA for CTEPH.", "<strong>Laboratory and etiologic panel</strong> — NT-proBNP (prognosis), ANA/scleroderma serologies, HIV, LFTs and abdominal imaging for portal hypertension, TSH.", "<strong>Right heart catheterization</strong> — confirm the diagnosis, phenotype (mPAP, PAWP, PVR, cardiac output by thermodilution and Fick), measure RA pressure and SvO2, perform vasoreactivity testing when indicated, and screen for shunt by oximetry."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 2, "text": "<strong>Mnemonic for the workup order.</strong> \"Every Lung Vein Right-hearts\": Echo, Lung tests (PFT/DLCO/CT), V/Q scan, then Right heart cath. The V/Q sits deliberately before the cath so CTEPH is never missed."}, {"type": "linkout", "depth": 1, "text": "Echocardiographic signs of RV pressure overload (D-shaped septum, RV dilation, McConnell sign in acute PE) and the CT appearance of an enlarged main PA (larger than the adjacent aorta) are best learned from labeled images.", "url": "https://radiopaedia.org/", "label": "RV overload and PA imaging (Radiopaedia)"}]}, {"id": "right-heart-cath", "title": "Right Heart Catheterization", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "RHC is the reference standard and is required before any PAH diagnosis or therapy. It is not merely a pressure measurement; it is a complete hemodynamic and prognostic assessment performed with meticulous technique."}, {"type": "list", "depth": 2, "head": ["A complete PAH-quality RHC records:"], "items": ["Right atrial pressure (a key prognostic variable), RV pressures, PA systolic/diastolic/mean", "PAWP (mean of several beats at end-expiration; confirm position and consider directly measured LVEDP if discordant)", "Cardiac output by BOTH thermodilution and indirect Fick (assumed O2 consumption), reconciling the two", "Calculated PVR and pulmonary vascular resistance index, transpulmonary and diastolic gradients", "Mixed venous oxygen saturation (SvO2) and a saturation run to screen for left-to-right shunt", "Vasoreactivity testing in eligible patients (see next section)"]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "<strong>Zero, level, and read at end-expiration.</strong> The transducer must be zeroed at the mid-thoracic (phlebostatic) line; read pressures at end-expiration to remove intrathoracic pressure swings. In obese or COPD patients with large respiratory swings, digital mean-of-cycle readings can overestimate the wedge. When thermodilution and Fick disagree substantially, favor Fick in low-output or significant TR states, and never accept a single discordant number that would change the WHO group without reconciling it."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 1, "text": "<strong>The wedge is the crux.</strong> Misreading a genuinely elevated wedge as normal converts Group 2 into a spurious Group 1 and exposes an HFpEF patient to vasodilators that can flash their lungs. If the wedge is borderline (13 to 16) or the clinical picture screams HFpEF, provoke with exercise or a fluid challenge before committing to a pre-capillary label."}]}, {"id": "vasoreactivity", "title": "Acute Vasoreactivity Testing", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Acute vasoreactivity testing (AVT) is performed at the diagnostic RHC in patients with IPAH, heritable PAH, or drug/toxin-induced PAH to identify the small minority (roughly 10% test acutely positive, and about half of those are durable responders) who may be treated with high-dose calcium channel blockers."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "label": "How AVT is done", "head": ["Agent", "Typical dose", "Notes"], "rows": [["Inhaled nitric oxide", "10 to 20 ppm for ~5 min", "First choice; selective pulmonary vasodilator, short-acting, safest"], ["IV epoprostenol", "IV titrated 2 to 12 ng/kg/min", "Alternative; systemic hypotension possible"], ["IV adenosine", "50 to 350 mcg/kg/min", "Alternative; flushing, chest tightness, AV block"], ["Inhaled iloprost", "2.5 to 5 mcg inhaled", "Acceptable alternative"]]}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 1, "entries": [{"term": "Positive response (Sitbon criteria)", "def": "A reduction in mPAP of at least 10 mmHg, reaching an absolute mPAP of 40 mmHg or lower, WITH an unchanged or increased cardiac output. All three conditions must be met."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "text": "<strong>Mnemonic.</strong> \"10-40-flow\": drop mPAP by at least 10, land at or below 40, and keep the flow (cardiac output preserved or up). Miss any one and the test is negative."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 2, "text": "<strong>Restrict AVT to the right patients.</strong> AVT is for IPAH/HPAH/drug-induced PAH only. Do NOT test (and do NOT give CCBs to) scleroderma-associated, portopulmonary, HIV, PVOD, or congenital-shunt PAH, or any Group 2/3 patient: CCBs can cause fatal hemodynamic collapse or pulmonary edema in these populations. Even in a positive responder, high-dose CCBs are begun cautiously with close hemodynamic follow-up, and roughly half lose their response over the first year and must be transitioned to PAH-specific therapy."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "label": "CCBs for confirmed acute responders", "head": ["Drug", "Typical target range", "When preferred"], "rows": [["Nifedipine (long-acting)", "up to 120 to 240 mg/day", "Higher resting heart rate acceptable"], ["Amlodipine", "up to 20 to 30 mg/day", "Common practical choice"], ["Diltiazem", "up to 240 to 720 mg/day", "Relative baseline tachycardia"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "Verapamil is avoided because of its negative inotropy on an already stressed RV. A patient started on CCBs must be reassessed (functional class, 6-minute walk, and repeat hemodynamics) within 3 to 4 months; only a sustained responder in functional class I to II with near-normal hemodynamics stays on CCB monotherapy."}]}, {"id": "pah-therapy-overview", "title": "Group 1 PAH: Therapeutic Strategy", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Once Group 1 PAH is confirmed and the rare CCB responder is excluded, therapy targets the three (now four) pathways. The modern paradigm is <strong>upfront combination therapy</strong> guided by risk stratification, escalated to parenteral prostacyclins and sotatercept as risk dictates, with early transplant referral for those who remain high-risk."}, {"type": "list", "depth": 1, "head": ["General measures for all PAH patients:"], "items": ["Supervised exercise/rehabilitation; avoid heavy isometric exertion", "Diuretics for RV volume overload; oxygen to keep saturation above 90%", "Pregnancy is strongly contraindicated (maternal mortality is high); ensure effective contraception (relevant to ERA teratogenicity)", "Routine immunizations; treat iron deficiency", "Referral to an expert PH center for anyone with confirmed or suspected Group 1 or 4 disease"]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 2, "text": "Anticoagulation, once routine in IPAH, is no longer broadly recommended given equivocal registry data and bleeding risk; it remains standard in CTEPH (lifelong) and is individualized elsewhere. Digoxin has a limited role. The therapeutic weight is on pathway-specific agents plus decongestion."}]}, {"id": "era", "title": "Endothelin Receptor Antagonists", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "ERAs block endothelin-1 at ET-A (and, for bosentan, ET-B) receptors, opposing vasoconstriction and proliferation. They are oral cornerstone agents, frequently paired with a PDE5 inhibitor as initial combination therapy (the AMBITION trial validated upfront ambrisentan plus tadalafil)."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "label": "Endothelin receptor antagonists", "head": ["Drug", "Start dose", "Target/usual dose", "Key contraindications", "Major side effects", "Monitoring"], "rows": [["Bosentan", "62.5 mg BID", "125 mg BID", "Pregnancy; concomitant glyburide or cyclosporine; moderate/severe hepatic impairment", "Hepatotoxicity (dose-dependent), peripheral edema, anemia; many CYP interactions (reduces hormonal contraceptive levels)", "Monthly LFTs; hemoglobin; pregnancy test. REMS enrollment"], ["Ambrisentan", "5 mg daily", "5 to 10 mg daily", "Pregnancy; idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis (worsens outcomes)", "Peripheral edema, nasal congestion, anemia; less hepatotoxicity than bosentan", "Periodic Hgb; pregnancy test. REMS"], ["Macitentan", "10 mg daily", "10 mg daily", "Pregnancy", "Anemia, headache, nasopharyngitis; low hepatotoxicity signal", "Hemoglobin; pregnancy test. REMS (SERAPHIN trial: morbidity/mortality benefit)"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 1, "text": "<strong>Teratogen — REMS and dual contraception.</strong> All ERAs are potent teratogens. In the United States they are dispensed only through a REMS program requiring documented negative monthly pregnancy tests and two reliable forms of contraception in women of childbearing potential. Bosentan additionally induces hormonal contraceptive metabolism, so hormonal contraception cannot be relied upon alone."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 2, "text": "<strong>Mnemonic — the ERA \"triple threat\": Liver, Limbs, Lineage.</strong> Liver = LFT monitoring (worst with bosentan); Limbs = peripheral edema; Lineage = teratogenicity plus anemia. And avoid ambrisentan in IPF, where the ARTEMIS-IPF trial showed increased disease progression and hospitalization."}]}, {"id": "no-pathway", "title": "NO-cGMP Pathway: PDE5 Inhibitors and sGC Stimulator", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "This pathway is targeted two ways: PDE5 inhibitors prevent cGMP breakdown, while riociguat stimulates soluble guanylate cyclase to raise cGMP independent of NO. Both increase cGMP-mediated pulmonary vasodilation and antiproliferation. They must never be combined."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "label": "NO-cGMP pathway agents", "head": ["Drug", "Start dose", "Target/usual dose", "Key contraindications", "Major side effects", "Monitoring"], "rows": [["Sildenafil (PDE5i)", "20 mg TID", "20 mg TID (higher doses not more effective, more AEs)", "Concurrent nitrates or riociguat; caution with alpha-blockers", "Headache, flushing, epistaxis, dyspepsia; rare NAION, hearing loss, priapism", "Clinical; blood pressure"], ["Tadalafil (PDE5i)", "20 mg daily", "40 mg daily", "Concurrent nitrates or riociguat", "As above; longer half-life", "Clinical; blood pressure"], ["Riociguat (sGC stimulator)", "1 mg TID", "up to 2.5 mg TID (titrate by SBP)", "Pregnancy; concurrent nitrates OR any PDE5 inhibitor; severe hypotension", "Hypotension, syncope, headache, dyspepsia, hemoptysis", "Blood pressure at each titration; pregnancy test (REMS)"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 1, "text": "<strong>Do NOT combine riociguat with a PDE5 inhibitor.</strong> The PATENT PLUS study of sildenafil plus riociguat was stopped for symptomatic hypotension with no benefit; the combination is contraindicated. Likewise, neither class may be given with nitrates. When switching a patient from sildenafil to riociguat, observe a washout (at least 24 hours off sildenafil, longer for tadalafil) before starting."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 2, "text": "<strong>Riociguat's two niches.</strong> It is uniquely approved for BOTH Group 1 PAH (PATENT-1) and inoperable or persistent/recurrent Group 4 CTEPH after endarterectomy (CHEST-1), the only PAH-pathway drug with a formal CTEPH indication. The REPLACE trial supports switching PDE5i inadequate responders to riociguat rather than merely adding a third drug."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 2, "text": "<strong>Mnemonic.</strong> \"Never stack the cGMP shop\": nitrates + PDE5i, PDE5i + riociguat, and riociguat + nitrates are each a hypotension trap. One cGMP-raising drug at a time."}]}, {"id": "prostacyclin", "title": "Prostacyclin Pathway", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Prostacyclin analogues and the oral IP-receptor agonist selexipag replace deficient prostacyclin signaling, producing potent vasodilation, platelet inhibition, and antiproliferation. Parenteral (IV/SC) prostacyclins remain the most effective therapy for the sickest patients; IV epoprostenol is the only PAH drug with a randomized survival benefit in advanced disease and anchors treatment of high-risk (functional class IV) patients."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "label": "Prostacyclin-pathway agents", "head": ["Drug", "Route", "Start / usual dosing", "Key cautions", "Major side effects", "Monitoring / notes"], "rows": [["Epoprostenol", "Continuous IV", "2 ng/kg/min, up-titrate; no fixed ceiling", "Half-life 3 to 6 min; abrupt interruption is life-threatening rebound PH", "Jaw pain, flushing, diarrhea, headache, leg pain; line infection, thrombosis", "Requires permanent central line and pump; survival benefit in FC IV"], ["Treprostinil", "IV, SC, inhaled, oral", "SC/IV titrated from ~1.25 ng/kg/min; inhaled 3 to 9 breaths QID", "Longer half-life (~4 h); SC site pain is common and limiting", "Infusion-site pain (SC), headache, GI, flushing", "Inhaled treprostinil is the ONLY drug approved for PH-ILD (Group 3, INCREASE trial)"], ["Iloprost", "Inhaled", "2.5 to 5 mcg, 6 to 9 times/day", "Short duration mandates frequent dosing", "Cough, flushing, jaw pain, hypotension", "Adherence-limited by dosing frequency"], ["Selexipag", "Oral (IP agonist)", "200 mcg BID, up-titrate to max 1600 mcg BID", "Not a prostacyclin analogue but same pathway", "Headache, jaw pain, diarrhea, flushing, myalgia", "GRIPHON trial: morbidity/mortality benefit; oral option to intensify"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 1, "text": "<strong>Never abruptly stop IV epoprostenol or IV treprostinil.</strong> The short half-life means a pump malfunction, line occlusion, or missed dose can trigger fatal rebound pulmonary hypertension within minutes to hours. Patients carry backup pumps and cassettes; admitted patients must have their infusion protected as a true emergency drug, never held for procedures without expert planning."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 2, "text": "<strong>Mnemonic for prostacyclin side effects.</strong> \"Jaw, Flush, Flow, Feet\": Jaw pain, Flushing/headache, Flow through the gut (diarrhea), and Feet/leg pain — plus SC site pain with subcutaneous treprostinil. These are pathway effects, expected, and managed by slow titration rather than discontinuation."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "Transitioning a deteriorating oral/inhaled patient to parenteral prostacyclin is a marker of high risk and should trigger simultaneous evaluation for lung transplantation. Do not wait for terminal RV failure; referral is a risk-based decision, not a last resort."}]}, {"id": "sotatercept", "title": "Sotatercept: The Activin-Signaling Inhibitor", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Sotatercept is a first-in-class activin signaling inhibitor: a fusion protein of the activin receptor type IIA extracellular domain and IgG Fc that acts as a ligand trap, sequestering activins and growth-differentiation factors that drive pulmonary vascular cell proliferation. It rebalances the pro-proliferative activin axis against the anti-proliferative BMPR2 axis, targeting remodeling rather than tone."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "label": "Sotatercept at a glance", "head": ["Property", "Detail"], "rows": [["Mechanism", "Activin ligand trap (ActRIIA-Fc); rebalances BMPR2 vs activin/GDF signaling — anti-remodeling"], ["Route/dose", "Subcutaneous every 3 weeks; start 0.3 mg/kg, target 0.7 mg/kg"], ["Indication", "Group 1 PAH, added to background therapy to improve exercise capacity, functional class, and reduce clinical worsening"], ["Landmark trials", "STELLAR (added to double/triple background therapy: improved 6-minute walk distance and multiple secondary endpoints); ZENITH studied high-risk (FC III/IV) patients and was stopped early for a morbidity/mortality benefit"], ["Key side effects", "Telangiectasias, epistaxis/bleeding, gingival bleeding, increased hemoglobin/erythrocytosis, thrombocytopenia, dizziness"], ["Monitoring", "CBC (hemoglobin and platelets) before each dose; hold/adjust for erythrocytosis or thrombocytopenia; pregnancy avoidance"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "<strong>Where sotatercept fits.</strong> In STELLAR it was added on top of established mono/dual/triple therapy, so it is currently an add-on for patients who remain intermediate- or high-risk despite background pathway therapy, not a replacement for it. Watch the hematologic effects: unlike vasodilators, it raises hemoglobin (mechanistically related to its erythropoietic ancestry) and can cause thrombocytopenia, so a CBC gates each dose. Telangiectasias and mucosal bleeding are the characteristic clinical signature."}, {"type": "linkout", "depth": 2, "text": "The STELLAR and ZENITH sotatercept trials and the mechanistic rationale are worth reading in full.", "url": "https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/", "label": "STELLAR / sotatercept trials (PubMed)"}]}, {"id": "risk-strat", "title": "Risk Stratification and Treatment Goals", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "PAH is managed to a low-risk state. Risk is estimated at baseline and, more importantly, at every follow-up using multiparameter tools; therapy is escalated until the patient reaches (and stays in) the low-risk category. The estimated one-year mortality corresponding to each stratum drives the aggressiveness of therapy."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "label": "Selected variables in ESC/ERS risk stratification", "head": ["Variable", "Low risk", "Intermediate", "High risk"], "rows": [["WHO functional class", "I-II", "III", "IV"], ["6-minute walk distance", ">440 m", "165-440 m", "<165 m"], ["NT-proBNP", "Low", "Intermediate", "High"], ["Right atrial pressure / RA area", "Normal/low", "Moderate", "Markedly elevated; pericardial effusion"], ["Cardiac index / SvO2", "Preserved", "Reduced", "Markedly reduced"], ["Estimated 1-yr mortality", "<5%", "5-20%", ">20%"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "text": "<strong>Mnemonic for follow-up risk.</strong> \"FT-4\": at each visit reassess <strong>F</strong>unctional class, <strong>T</strong>-walk (6-minute walk), and the two <strong>4</strong>-strata engines — the ESC/ERS 4-strata model and a REVEAL-based score. The 2022 guideline uses a simplified follow-up tool built mainly on FC, 6MWD, and NT-proBNP to sort patients into low/intermediate-low/intermediate-high/high."}, {"type": "p", "depth": 2, "text": "The abridged follow-up tool (three noninvasive variables: WHO FC, 6MWD, and BNP/NT-proBNP) yields a four-stratum output. REVEAL 2.0 and its abbreviated REVEAL Lite 2 are validated US registry-derived alternatives. The goal is unchanged across tools: get the patient to low risk and keep them there, escalating therapy whenever they are not."}]}, {"id": "combination-treatment-algorithm", "title": "Combination Therapy and the Treatment Algorithm", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "The modern standard for most Group 1 patients without significant cardiopulmonary comorbidities is initial combination therapy, then escalation guided by follow-up risk. Sequential monotherapy is reserved for the CCB responder and for patients with substantial left-heart or lung comorbidity in whom aggressive vasodilation is risky."}, {"type": "steps", "depth": 1, "head": ["Practical treatment sequence"], "items": ["Confirm Group 1 PAH by RHC; perform AVT in IPAH/HPAH/drug-induced disease.", "<strong>Acute responder</strong> → high-dose CCB with reassessment at 3 to 4 months; continue only if sustained low-risk response.", "<strong>Low or intermediate risk, non-responder</strong> → upfront oral dual combination (ERA + PDE5 inhibitor; AMBITION supports ambrisentan + tadalafil).", "<strong>High risk at baseline</strong> → include a parenteral prostacyclin (e.g., IV epoprostenol or treprostinil) in initial triple therapy and refer for transplant evaluation.", "<strong>Reassess at follow-up:</strong> if not low risk, escalate — add the third pathway (prostacyclin/selexipag), add or switch to riociguat, and/or add sotatercept.", "<strong>Persistent intermediate/high risk on maximal therapy</strong> → escalate to parenteral prostacyclin if not already used, and proceed with lung (or heart-lung) transplant evaluation."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "<strong>Two escalation levers beyond \"add a drug.\"</strong> First, the REPLACE data support switching an inadequately responding PDE5i to riociguat rather than only adding agents. Second, sotatercept (STELLAR) provides an anti-remodeling add-on for those stuck at intermediate/high risk. Both are tools to move a patient toward low risk without simply stacking vasodilators indefinitely."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 2, "text": "Patients with \"atypical\" phenotypes — multiple HFpEF risk factors, low DLCO, older age, cardiopulmonary comorbidity — may tolerate and benefit from only monotherapy started cautiously, because full combination vasodilation can unmask occult left-heart disease or worsen gas exchange. Match aggressiveness to phenotype."}]}, {"id": "group2", "title": "Group 2: PH Due to Left Heart Disease", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Group 2 is the most common cause of PH. The physiology is passive backward transmission of elevated left atrial pressure (isolated post-capillary, IpcPH), sometimes with superimposed pulmonary vascular remodeling (combined post- and pre-capillary, CpcPH, defined by PVR >2 WU). The treatment is optimization of the left heart, not the pulmonary vasculature."}, {"type": "list", "depth": 1, "head": ["Management principles:"], "items": ["Treat the underlying disease: guideline-directed medical therapy for HFrEF; decongestion, blood pressure, weight, sleep apnea, and rate/rhythm control for HFpEF; correct significant valvular lesions.", "Aggressive volume management to lower left atrial and wedge pressure.", "Do NOT use PAH-specific vasodilators outside of a trial."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 1, "text": "<strong>Why not vasodilate Group 2.</strong> Pulmonary vasodilators increase pulmonary blood flow into a stiff, high-pressure left heart that cannot accommodate it, precipitating flash pulmonary edema. Trials of PDE5 inhibitors and ERAs in HFpEF-PH and post-capillary disease have been neutral or harmful. The correct response to \"PH on echo\" in a patient with a big left atrium and diastolic dysfunction is to treat the heart failure and re-image, not to reach for sildenafil."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "CpcPH (post-capillary PH with PVR >2 WU) identifies a higher-risk Group 2 subset with a pulmonary vascular component, and is an active research area — but current guidelines still do not endorse routine PAH therapy for it outside trials. Reserve it for expert centers and protocols."}]}, {"id": "group3", "title": "Group 3: PH Due to Lung Disease and Hypoxia", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "In chronic lung disease, PH is usually mild and proportionate to the parenchymal and hypoxic burden, driven by hypoxic pulmonary vasoconstriction and capillary bed destruction. The therapeutic priorities are the lung disease and oxygenation, not the pulmonary vessels."}, {"type": "list", "depth": 1, "head": ["Management priorities:"], "items": ["Optimize the underlying disease (bronchodilators, antifibrotics, pulmonary rehab).", "<strong>Long-term supplemental oxygen</strong> for chronic hypoxemia — the one intervention that reliably blunts hypoxic vasoconstriction.", "Treat sleep-disordered breathing and hypoventilation (CPAP/BiPAP).", "Referral to an expert center for \"severe\" Group 3 PH (markedly elevated PVR with a mild parenchymal burden), where the phenotype may overlap PAH."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 1, "text": "<strong>Vasodilators worsen hypoxemia in Group 3.</strong> Systemic PAH vasodilators blunt hypoxic pulmonary vasoconstriction indiscriminately, redirecting blood to poorly ventilated lung units, worsening V/Q mismatch and hypoxemia. This is why oral sildenafil is not used for COPD- or ILD-related PH."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 2, "text": "<strong>The one exception.</strong> The INCREASE trial showed <strong>inhaled treprostinil</strong> improved 6-minute walk distance in PH associated with interstitial lung disease (PH-ILD), and it is FDA-approved for that specific indication. Inhaled delivery may preserve V/Q matching better than systemic agents. This is a carefully bounded exception, applied at expert centers to a defined phenotype — not license to vasodilate Group 3 broadly."}]}, {"id": "group4-cteph", "title": "Group 4: CTEPH — The Curable One", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Chronic thromboembolic pulmonary hypertension results from organized, fibrotic thromboembolic material obstructing the pulmonary arteries after incompletely resolved (often clinically silent) pulmonary embolism. It is the one form of PH that can be surgically cured, which is why every pre-capillary PH workup must include a V/Q scan and why suspected CTEPH goes to an expert center."}, {"type": "steps", "depth": 1, "head": ["CTEPH pathway"], "items": ["Screen persistently dyspneic PE survivors (and all pre-capillary PH) with a <strong>V/Q scan</strong> — a normal scan excludes CTEPH; mismatched segmental defects are the signature.", "Confirm and map disease with CT pulmonary angiography and, at the center, invasive pulmonary angiography plus RHC.", "<strong>Lifelong anticoagulation</strong> for all CTEPH patients.", "Multidisciplinary operability assessment: proximal, surgically accessible disease → <strong>pulmonary endarterectomy (PEA)</strong>, the potentially curative treatment of choice.", "Inoperable disease, or persistent/recurrent PH after PEA → <strong>riociguat</strong> (CHEST-1) and/or <strong>balloon pulmonary angioplasty (BPA)</strong> at expert centers."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "text": "<strong>Pearl.</strong> Riociguat is the only PAH-pathway drug formally approved for CTEPH (inoperable or persistent/recurrent after PEA). Everything else in Group 4 is surgery, BPA, and anticoagulation — do not reflexively treat CTEPH like IPAH, and never label CTEPH inoperable without an expert surgical opinion."}, {"type": "linkout", "depth": 2, "text": "The V/Q mismatch pattern of CTEPH and the appearance of chronic organized thrombus (webs, bands, pouch defects) on imaging reward a labeled review.", "url": "https://radiopaedia.org/", "label": "CTEPH imaging patterns (Radiopaedia)"}]}, {"id": "group5-special", "title": "Group 5 and Special Situations", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Group 5 is a heterogeneous \"multifactorial\" bin where the mechanism is unclear or mixed and PAH-specific therapy has no established role; management is of the underlying disorder at an expert center."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 2, "entries": [{"term": "Hematologic", "def": "Chronic hemolytic anemia (sickle cell), myeloproliferative disorders, chronic splenectomy state."}, {"term": "Systemic/metabolic", "def": "Sarcoidosis, pulmonary Langerhans cell histiocytosis, neurofibromatosis; glycogen storage disease, Gaucher, thyroid disease."}, {"term": "Others", "def": "Chronic kidney disease on dialysis, fibrosing mediastinitis, complex congenital heart disease, tumor thrombotic microangiopathy."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "<strong>Sarcoid-associated PH</strong> is a common Group 5 consult and is mechanistically mixed (fibrotic vascular involvement, extrinsic compression by adenopathy, parenchymal disease, and left-heart involvement). It is managed individually at expert centers, sometimes with cautious PAH therapy under protocol — a reminder that Group 5 is a call for careful mechanistic reasoning, not an algorithm."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 2, "text": "<strong>Pregnancy in PAH.</strong> Pregnancy carries very high maternal mortality in PAH and is contraindicated. Counsel effective contraception (remembering bosentan reduces hormonal contraceptive efficacy), and manage any pregnancy that occurs at an expert center with a plan for the peripartum RV. ERAs, riociguat, and several agents are teratogenic."}]}, {"id": "trials-frontier", "title": "Landmark Trials and the Frontier", "body": [{"type": "table", "depth": 2, "label": "Trials worth knowing by name", "head": ["Trial", "Drug / question", "Take-home"], "rows": [["AMBITION", "Upfront ambrisentan + tadalafil vs monotherapy", "Established initial oral combination therapy in PAH"], ["SERAPHIN", "Macitentan, event-driven", "First long-term morbidity/mortality benefit with an ERA"], ["GRIPHON", "Selexipag (oral IP agonist)", "Reduced morbidity/mortality events, added to background therapy"], ["PATENT-1 / CHEST-1", "Riociguat in PAH / in CTEPH", "Efficacy in PAH and in inoperable/persistent CTEPH"], ["INCREASE", "Inhaled treprostinil in PH-ILD", "Improved 6MWD; basis for the Group 3 PH-ILD indication"], ["STELLAR / ZENITH", "Sotatercept added to background / in high-risk PAH", "Anti-remodeling activin trap improves exercise capacity and outcomes"], ["REPLACE", "Switch PDE5i to riociguat vs continue", "Supports switching inadequate PDE5i responders to riociguat"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "<strong>Where the field is heading.</strong> The center of gravity is shifting from pure vasodilation toward reverse-remodeling: sotatercept is the proof of concept, and BMPR2-restorative and anti-proliferative strategies are in trials. Risk-based treat-to-target management, earlier parenteral therapy, and earlier transplant referral for non-low-risk patients define contemporary practice. The unifying idea across all of it remains the same — protect and unload the right ventricle."}, {"type": "list", "depth": 1, "head": ["High-yield closing rules:"], "items": ["Phenotype before you prescribe: mPAP >20, then PAWP and PVR, then WHO group.", "Group 1 is treated by pathways and risk; Groups 2 and 3 by treating the underlying disease; Group 4 by surgery/BPA and anticoagulation.", "Never combine a PDE5 inhibitor with riociguat or a nitrate.", "ERAs are teratogens under REMS with LFT and hemoglobin monitoring.", "Never abruptly stop a parenteral prostacyclin.", "The right ventricle is the patient — treat coupling, not the pressure."]}]}], "quiz": [{"stem": "A 46-year-old woman with limited cutaneous systemic sclerosis reports 8 months of progressive exertional dyspnea. Echo estimates a PASP of 62 mmHg with a dilated, hypokinetic right ventricle and flattened interventricular septum. PFTs show preserved lung volumes with an isolated DLCO of 44% predicted. Chest CT shows no significant parenchymal fibrosis. What is the most appropriate next step?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Start ambrisentan and tadalafil empirically"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Obtain a ventilation/perfusion scan and proceed to right heart catheterization"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Begin high-dose amlodipine"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Start long-term oxygen and reassess in 6 months"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Refer directly for lung transplantation"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "Echo raises pretest probability but never establishes the diagnosis. Before any therapy, CTEPH must be excluded with a V/Q scan and the diagnosis confirmed and phenotyped by RHC (mPAP, PAWP, PVR, cardiac output). Empiric PAH therapy (A) and CCBs (C) precede confirmation and, in scleroderma, AVT/CCBs are not indicated. The isolated low DLCO with preserved volumes is a classic scleroderma-PAH clue but still requires catheter confirmation."}, {"stem": "During diagnostic right heart catheterization for suspected idiopathic PAH, a patient's baseline mPAP is 58 mmHg with a cardiac output of 3.9 L/min. After inhaled nitric oxide at 20 ppm, mPAP falls to 39 mmHg and cardiac output rises to 4.4 L/min. Which of the following is the most appropriate interpretation and next step?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Negative test; start combination ERA plus PDE5 inhibitor"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Positive test; begin a high-dose calcium channel blocker with planned reassessment"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Positive test; begin IV epoprostenol"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Indeterminate; repeat testing with adenosine"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Positive test; begin riociguat plus sildenafil"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "A positive acute vasoreactivity test (Sitbon criteria) requires a fall in mPAP of at least 10 mmHg to an absolute value of 40 mmHg or lower with preserved or increased cardiac output. Here mPAP dropped 19 mmHg to 39 with a higher output — all three criteria met. In IPAH, this identifies a candidate for high-dose CCB therapy, followed by mandatory reassessment at 3 to 4 months since about half lose their response. Riociguat plus sildenafil (E) is an absolutely contraindicated combination."}, {"stem": "A 72-year-old man with long-standing hypertension, obesity, atrial fibrillation, and exertional dyspnea has an echo showing normal LV ejection fraction, grade 2 diastolic dysfunction, a dilated left atrium, and estimated PASP 55 mmHg. Right heart catheterization shows mPAP 34 mmHg, PAWP 20 mmHg, PVR 2.5 WU. Which management strategy is most appropriate?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Start sildenafil to lower pulmonary pressures"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Start macitentan and refer to a PAH center for combination therapy"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Optimize heart failure and comorbidity management (diuresis, blood pressure, rhythm, weight, sleep apnea)"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Start high-dose calcium channel blocker"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Begin inhaled treprostinil"}], "correct": "C", "explanation": "PAWP of 20 mmHg makes this post-capillary (Group 2) PH due to HFpEF; the elevated PVR indicates a combined post- and pre-capillary component but does not change the fundamental strategy. Group 2 PH is treated by optimizing the left heart and comorbidities, not by PAH vasodilators, which can precipitate flash pulmonary edema and have been neutral-to-harmful in trials. PAH-specific drugs (A, B, D, E) are inappropriate outside of a trial."}, {"stem": "A patient with idiopathic PAH on background ambrisentan and tadalafil is being escalated. The team considers adding riociguat. Which statement is correct?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Riociguat can be safely added to tadalafil for additive cGMP effect"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Riociguat plus a PDE5 inhibitor is contraindicated due to symptomatic hypotension"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Riociguat should replace the ambrisentan"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Riociguat requires monthly liver function testing as its principal safety concern"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Riociguat is only approved for CTEPH, not PAH"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "Riociguat (an sGC stimulator) and PDE5 inhibitors both raise cGMP; the PATENT PLUS study of the combination was stopped for symptomatic hypotension with no benefit, and co-administration is contraindicated. If riociguat is desired, the PDE5 inhibitor must be stopped with an appropriate washout (REPLACE supports switching rather than adding). Riociguat is approved for BOTH PAH and CTEPH (E is wrong). Its main safety issues are hypotension and teratogenicity (REMS), not LFTs (D)."}, {"stem": "A 60-year-old woman with interstitial lung disease has worsening dyspnea. RHC confirms pre-capillary PH (mPAP 32, PAWP 11, PVR 4 WU) attributable to her lung disease. High-resolution CT shows moderate fibrosis. Which therapy has demonstrated benefit in this specific setting?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Oral sildenafil"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Ambrisentan"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Inhaled treprostinil"}, {"key": "D", "text": "IV epoprostenol"}, {"key": "E", "text": "High-dose calcium channel blocker"}], "correct": "C", "explanation": "This is Group 3 PH associated with ILD (PH-ILD). The INCREASE trial showed inhaled treprostinil improved 6-minute walk distance in PH-ILD, and it is the FDA-approved option for this indication, likely because inhaled delivery better preserves V/Q matching. Systemic vasodilators such as sildenafil (A) and ambrisentan (B) worsen hypoxemia by blunting hypoxic vasoconstriction; ambrisentan specifically worsened outcomes in IPF. CCBs (E) have no role here."}, {"stem": "A 55-year-old man has persistent exertional dyspnea 6 months after an acute pulmonary embolism. Echo shows RV dilation with elevated PASP. A V/Q scan reveals multiple bilateral mismatched segmental perfusion defects. RHC confirms pre-capillary PH. What is the most important next step?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Start ambrisentan plus tadalafil"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Refer to an expert center for operability assessment and consideration of pulmonary endarterectomy"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Discontinue anticoagulation and start aspirin"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Begin high-dose calcium channel blocker"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Start inhaled treprostinil"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "Mismatched segmental defects on V/Q with confirmed pre-capillary PH after PE indicate CTEPH (Group 4) — the one potentially curable form. All CTEPH patients need lifelong anticoagulation (so C is wrong), and the priority is referral to an expert center for operability assessment, since pulmonary endarterectomy is potentially curative for surgically accessible disease. Riociguat and balloon pulmonary angioplasty are for inoperable or residual disease; generic PAH combination therapy and CCBs are not the answer."}], "references": ["2022 ESC/ERS Guidelines for the diagnosis and treatment of pulmonary hypertension (European Heart Journal)", "Proceedings of the 6th World Symposium on Pulmonary Hypertension (Simonneau et al., updated hemodynamic definitions and clinical classification)", "AMBITION trial: initial combination therapy with ambrisentan plus tadalafil in pulmonary arterial hypertension", "SERAPHIN trial: macitentan for the treatment of pulmonary arterial hypertension", "GRIPHON trial: selexipag for the treatment of pulmonary arterial hypertension", "CHEST-1 and PATENT-1 trials: riociguat in CTEPH and in pulmonary arterial hypertension", "PATENT PLUS study: riociguat plus sildenafil in PAH (terminated for hypotension)", "REPLACE trial: switching from a PDE5 inhibitor to riociguat in PAH", "INCREASE trial: inhaled treprostinil in pulmonary hypertension due to interstitial lung disease", "STELLAR trial: sotatercept for the treatment of pulmonary arterial hypertension", "ZENITH trial: sotatercept in high-risk pulmonary arterial hypertension", "ARTEMIS-IPF trial: ambrisentan in idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis (increased progression)", "ACCP/CHEST and AHA guideline statements on pulmonary embolism follow-up and CTEPH evaluation"]};
